`Fiber.interrupt` sends a structured interrupt signal that the runtime delivers at the fiber's next suspension point (sleep, async boundary, yield*). Unlike cancelling a `Promise` (which is non-standard and cooperative at best), interrupt runs the fiber's finalizers — any scoped resources are released before the fiber exits.

```ts
import { Effect, Fiber, Data } from "effect";

class WorkerError extends Data.TaggedError("WorkerError")<{ readonly worker: string }> {}

declare const workerA: Effect.Effect<number, WorkerError>;
declare const workerB: Effect.Effect<number, WorkerError>;

export const conditionalStop = (
  stopB: boolean
): Effect.Effect<number, WorkerError> =>
  Effect.gen(function* () {
    const fa = yield* Effect.fork(workerA);
    const fb = yield* Effect.fork(workerB);
    if (stopB) {
      yield* Fiber.interrupt(fb);
    }
    const a = yield* Fiber.join(fa);
    if (!stopB) {
      yield* Fiber.interrupt(fb);
    }
    return a;
  });
```

The example shows interrupt as a normal effectful step. After the conditional interrupt, the program continues — interrupted fibers' results are not observed.

```ts
import { Effect, Data } from "effect";

class LocalMiss extends Data.TaggedError("LocalMiss")<{}> {}
class RegionalError extends Data.TaggedError("RegionalError")<{ readonly region: string }> {}
class GlobalError extends Data.TaggedError("GlobalError")<{}> {}

interface Blob { readonly bytes: Uint8Array; readonly from: string }

declare const local: (k: string) => Effect.Effect<Blob, LocalMiss>;
declare const regional: (k: string) => Effect.Effect<Blob, RegionalError>;
declare const globalCdn: (k: string) => Effect.Effect<Blob, GlobalError>;

export const fetchBlob = (
  key: string
): Effect.Effect<Blob, LocalMiss | RegionalError | GlobalError> =>
  Effect.gen(function* () {
    return yield* Effect.raceAll([local(key), regional(key), globalCdn(key)]);
  });
```

The local source usually wins by a wide margin; when it misses, regional or global can still finish the race. The typed error union captures every possible failure path, letting downstream code discriminate with `catchTag` per source.

```ts
import { Effect, Duration, Data } from "effect";

export class TimedOut extends Data.TaggedError("TimedOut")<{ readonly ms: number; readonly op: string }> {}

export const raceTimeout = <A, E, R>(
  op: string,
  ms: number,
  effect: Effect.Effect<A, E, R>
): Effect.Effect<A, E | TimedOut, R> =>
  Effect.race(
    effect,
    Effect.sleep(Duration.millis(ms)).pipe(
      Effect.flatMap(() => Effect.fail(new TimedOut({ ms, op })))
    )
  );

declare const uploadFile: (path: string) => Effect.Effect<string>;

export const uploadBounded = (path: string) =>
  raceTimeout("upload", 5000, uploadFile(path));
```

The helper is fully generic over the wrapped effect's `A`, `E`, `R`, so every caller gets a typed `E | TimedOut` error channel. When the deadline wins, the runtime interrupts the wrapped upload — no orphaned I/O.

```ts
import { Effect, Fiber, Data } from "effect";

class RequestError extends Data.TaggedError("RequestError")<{ readonly url: string }> {}

declare const longRequest: (url: string) => Effect.Effect<string, RequestError>;

export const startRequest = (url: string) =>
  Effect.gen(function* () {
    return yield* Effect.fork(longRequest(url));
  });
export const abort = (f: Fiber.Fiber<string, RequestError>) => Fiber.interrupt(f);
```

The fiber handle plays the role of `AbortController`; `Fiber.interrupt` plays the role of `AbortSignal.abort()`. The key difference is structural: when the enclosing effect scope ends, the runtime interrupts the fiber automatically — no need for `try { } finally { controller.abort() }`.

```ts
import { Effect, Fiber, Data } from "effect";

class FetchError extends Data.TaggedError("FetchError")<{ readonly key: string }> {}

interface Payload { readonly key: string; readonly data: string }

declare const fetchKey: (key: string) => Effect.Effect<Payload, FetchError>;
declare const waitForChoice: Effect.Effect<string>;

export const speculative = (
  guessedKey: string
): Effect.Effect<Payload, FetchError> =>
  Effect.gen(function* () {
    const fiber = yield* Effect.fork(fetchKey(guessedKey));
    const actual = yield* waitForChoice;
    if (actual === guessedKey) {
      return yield* Fiber.join(fiber);
    }
    yield* Fiber.interrupt(fiber);
    return yield* fetchKey(actual);
  });
```

If the user confirms the guess, the forked fetch is already in-flight so the join returns quickly. If the guess was wrong, `Fiber.interrupt` cancels the speculative work before we issue the correct request — no wasted bandwidth on the wrong key.

```ts
import { Effect, Fiber, Data } from "effect";

class JobError extends Data.TaggedError("JobError")<{ readonly id: number }> {}

declare const runJob: (id: number) => Effect.Effect<string, JobError>;

export const runPool = (
  ids: ReadonlyArray<number>
): Effect.Effect<ReadonlyArray<string>, JobError> =>
  Effect.gen(function* () {
    const fibers: ReadonlyArray<Fiber.Fiber<string, JobError>> = yield* Effect.forEach(
      ids,
      (id) => Effect.fork(runJob(id))
    );
    const results: string[] = [];
    for (const f of fibers) {
      const r = yield* Fiber.join(f);
      results.push(r);
    }
    return results;
  });
```

Every job starts on its own fiber immediately; the loop joins them in submission order so we can build the result array in a predictable shape. If any job fails the parent fails and the remaining fibers are interrupted by the runtime.

`Effect.race(a, b)` starts both effects on child fibers of the current scope. Whichever finishes first wins and returns its value; the losing fiber is interrupted by the runtime and any finalizers run to release resources. If the parent is interrupted, both children are interrupted — that's the structural part.

```ts
import { Effect, Duration, Data } from "effect";

class DbError extends Data.TaggedError("DbError")<{ readonly query: string }> {}
class Slow extends Data.TaggedError("Slow")<{ readonly ms: number }> {}

interface Row { readonly id: string; readonly name: string }

declare const query: (sql: string) => Effect.Effect<Row, DbError>;

export const quickQuery = (
  sql: string
): Effect.Effect<Row, DbError | Slow> =>
  Effect.race(
    query(sql),
    Effect.sleep(Duration.millis(500)).pipe(
      Effect.flatMap(() => Effect.fail(new Slow({ ms: 500 })))
    )
  );
```

When `Slow` fires, the in-flight DB query is interrupted — its connection-cleanup finalizer runs before the typed `Slow` error reaches the caller.

```ts
import { Effect, Fiber, Ref, Data } from "effect";

class WorkerError extends Data.TaggedError("WorkerError")<{ readonly idx: number }> {}

const worker = (
  idx: number,
  acc: Ref.Ref<ReadonlyArray<number>>
): Effect.Effect<void, WorkerError> =>
  Effect.gen(function* () {
    const v = idx * 2;
    yield* Ref.update(acc, (xs) => [...xs, v]);
  });

export const collect = (
  n: number
): Effect.Effect<ReadonlyArray<number>, WorkerError> =>
  Effect.gen(function* () {
    const acc = yield* Ref.make<ReadonlyArray<number>>([]);
    const fibers: Fiber.Fiber<void, WorkerError>[] = [];
    for (let i = 0; i < n; i++) {
      fibers.push(yield* Effect.fork(worker(i, acc)));
    }
    for (const f of fibers) {
      yield* Fiber.join(f);
    }
    return yield* Ref.get(acc);
  });
```

`Ref.update` is atomic, so concurrent pushes don't lose entries. The order in the final array depends on fiber scheduling — use a `Queue` if you need FIFO ordering.

```ts
import { Effect, Duration, Data } from "effect";

class PrimaryError extends Data.TaggedError("PrimaryError")<{ readonly url: string }> {}
class CacheEmpty extends Data.TaggedError("CacheEmpty")<{ readonly key: string }> {}
class Deadline extends Data.TaggedError("Deadline")<{ readonly ms: number }> {}

interface Doc { readonly id: string; readonly source: "primary" | "cache" }

declare const primary: Effect.Effect<Doc, PrimaryError>;
declare const staleCache: Effect.Effect<Doc, CacheEmpty>;

export const firstGoodEnough = (
  staleAfter: number,
  hardDeadline: number
): Effect.Effect<Doc, PrimaryError | CacheEmpty | Deadline> =>
  Effect.raceAll([
    primary,
    Effect.sleep(Duration.millis(staleAfter)).pipe(
      Effect.flatMap(() => staleCache)
    ),
    Effect.sleep(Duration.millis(hardDeadline)).pipe(
      Effect.flatMap(() => Effect.fail(new Deadline({ ms: hardDeadline })))
    ),
  ]);
```

The primary fires first; after `staleAfter` the cache read is allowed in; the hard deadline is the safety net. `raceAll` returns the first success, interrupting the other two fibers.

```ts
import { Effect, Fiber, Duration, Data } from "effect";

class SubError extends Data.TaggedError("SubError")<{ readonly topic: string }> {}
class Deadline extends Data.TaggedError("Deadline")<{ readonly ms: number }> {}

interface Message { readonly topic: string; readonly body: string }

declare const subscribe: (topic: string) => Effect.Effect<Message, SubError>;

export const supervised = (
  topic: string,
  deadlineMs: number
): Effect.Effect<{ readonly fiber: Fiber.Fiber<Message, SubError | Deadline> }> =>
  Effect.gen(function* () {
    const raced = Effect.race(
      subscribe(topic),
      Effect.sleep(Duration.millis(deadlineMs)).pipe(
        Effect.flatMap(() => Effect.fail(new Deadline({ ms: deadlineMs })))
      )
    );
    const fiber = yield* Effect.fork(raced);
    return { fiber };
  });

export const stop = <A, E>(f: Fiber.Fiber<A, E>) => Fiber.interrupt(f);
```

The race already supports automatic cancellation on deadline; wrapping it in `Effect.fork` also lets an external `Fiber.interrupt` stop the whole thing early. Both cancellation paths run the subscription's finalizers cleanly.
